Write a custom collector to join strings with a dash (-).

Input:
List<String> items = Arrays.asList("A", "B", "C");

Solutions:-

Java 8 custom collector joins strings with dash using Collector.of() implementing all required SPI methods. For input ["A", "B", "C"], produces "A-B-C".

#Step-by-Step Logic
Create Collector.of(supplier, accumulator, combiner, finisher).

Supplier: "" (empty string identity)

Accumulator: Add to result with dash if not first

Combiner: Merge parallel results without double dash

Finisher: Return result unchanged

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.List;
import java.util.stream.Collector;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;
import java.util.Arrays;

public class DashJoinCollector {
    public static Collector<String, StringBuilder, String> dashJoining() {
        return Collector.of(
            StringBuilder::new,                                    // supplier
            (builder, str) -> {                                    // accumulator
                if (builder.length() > 0) builder.append("-");
                builder.append(str);
            },
            (left, right) -> {                                     // combiner
                if (left.length() == 0) return right;
                if (right.length() == 0) return left;
                return left.append("-").append(right);
            },                                                     // finisher
            StringBuilder::toString                                // finisher
        );
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> items = Arrays.asList("A", "B", "C");
        String result = items.stream()
                            .collect(dashJoining());
        System.out.println(result);  // A-B-C
    }
}

Another Approach:-
String joined = items.stream().collect(
    Collector.of(
        () -> new StringBuilder(),
        (sb, s) -> { if (sb.length() > 0) sb.append('-'); sb.append(s); },
        (sb1, sb2) -> { if (sb1.length() > 0 && sb2.length() > 0) sb1.append('-'); sb1.append(sb2); return sb1; },
        StringBuilder::toString
    )
);
System.out.println(joined);


#Thought Process
StringBuilder mutable accumulator avoids String immutability overhead. Combiner handles parallel execution by checking existing content. Method reference StringBuilder::toString clean finisher. length()>0 detects first element avoiding leading dash.

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty list: Empty StringBuilder → ""
Single element: No dash → original string
Null elements: NPE in append(null)
Null list: NPE on stream()
Parallel streams: Combiner ensures single dash between sub-results
Large lists: Efficient O(n) StringBuilder operations
